The crowds at Chinese offices in the United States are therefore comparable to the Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you don't want to wait in long lines for it, you have to pay $100 and more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study in the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and is home to less than one percent of the country's population, was visited by 1.8 million Americans.
China often exacerbates this problem by using the tourism industry to further its political goals, such as in its disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut off transportation to South Korea in the spring as part of a row over South Korea's missile defense system, the South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, visits dropped 42 percent year- on- year, while Japan recorded an 85 percent increase.
All of these affect macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent report by the US Federal Reserve, up to $190 billion could be lost to China as a result of Chinese travel, while China will gain about $35 billion a year from selling currency to tourists.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of 217 billion dollars in tourism last year, which is equivalent to 44 percent of China's total surplus in trade in goods.
The low number of tourists, therefore, is a very painful blow to a country that anxiously prevents capital inflow.
However, the factors mentioned above are only one manifestation of a more general reluctance to talk to foreigners.
In many parts of China, immigrants are virtually unheard of.
As recently as 2013, there were less than a million foreigners living in China.
Some cities in the United States have even more.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
Indeed, a number of scientific papers show that immigrants tend to stimulate economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
But in China, you're not going to find them.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is being proposed is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made a major effort to simplify and reduce visa costs.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
