In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruled that the black people of Georgia were eligible to vote in elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
And just in time for the summer election, the FBI says black farmer Roger Malcolm stabbed white landowner Barnett Hester in a brawl allegedly over his wife.
According to Brooks, there was a town legend that Hester had sex with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and had her in a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, a prominent white-colored landowner named Loy Harrison posted a $600 bond for Malcolm.
