The NHS is prescribing a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will be given access to 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September on the basis of the Supreme Court's decision on NHS funding.
The National Health Service (NSH) of England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients over a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a high court ruling last year that the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite stating that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England's Director General, Simon Stevens, as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients, with more clinics joining in October and full implementation across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of getting HIV.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there is enough of the specific medication in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign a consent form to participate in the trial, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also go to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in the trial.
The programme will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international public tender.
The pilot period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years of efforts to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: "We are witnessing a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and to patients at risk, it offers the potential to turn the tide of the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require partner persuasion, resulting in improved quality of life for many.
We welcome this declaration.'
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust said: "The number one priority must be rapid deployment of the test nationwide; we need to ensure it is available to every patient.
We now have a trial PrEP drug and are well on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of government delays and hold-ups.
The evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
The follow-up tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect those who are exposed to HIV and together to end the spread of HIV in society.'
