I was looking for something a little more reasonable.
I came across this flat in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I fell in love with him right away and I nodded to him that very day.
Since then, the 1,000-square-meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
A one-room apartment with a complicated layout - you had to go through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
I wanted a high ceiling, big windows, lots of light.
That was my demand, she said.
To do this, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill-based design and engineering firm Duck & Shed and used the nearly four-meter ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but a place to live.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two openings - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine that could be walked up.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated", he explained.
We had to arrange both rooms so that we could walk upright.
It was not only a simple platform, but also a steel structure, bent to the right height above and below the ceiling.
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - while adding to the drama.
In the middle floor, looking out on the magnificent living room, the old copper window frames in the Retrouvius design.
The mirror furniture in gold, the silver lines and the retro chandelier of Serge Mouille create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in dramaticity, space and lighting.
The short corridor is lined with mirrors on both sides, making it look longer.
The mirror rack in the kitchen looks like a window to another room.
There are storage rooms with mirrors for storing utensils and glasses at the entrance doors.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a much larger space, is that it can be separated from the kitchen when it is not in use.
Closed kitchens are nothing new.
But what's unique about this solution is the folding doors.
"We had to solve the technical problem", says Erfan, "of reinforced air doors.
The doors are fitted with counterweights to make them easy to unlock.
Through clever use of space and storage, Joanne gained an additional 40 square feet, a second bedroom, and a better overall layout.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is the living space - or the appreciation of your property", Erfan said.
The real estate agent basically calculates the estimated price of the apartment based on the living area when entering the apartment.
In this case, the living space was increased while maintaining the quality of the materials that give the space a luxurious appearance.
"The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with the home", Erfan added.
You don't like electrical connections in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they don't win your heart.
As it turns out, good design and living space enhancement can turn an ordinary apartment into an extraordinary work of art.
And like Joanne, you can choose to stay, eventually.
