A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using DNA from Chelsea Manning
In the center of a room at New York's Friedman Gallery, there are several faces of different colors - white, black, and brown - hanging from the ceiling on wires, each one as if out of sight of the one before it.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from a scrape of her mouth and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally leaking classified cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before he left office as U.S. president.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to depict what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the malleability of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken about identifying as a woman since her youth. She was convicted in 2013 on twenty charges, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud, and theft.
All of her photographs were retained by prison staff, with only one black and white photograph of lower quality, showing Manning, visibly concerned, sitting in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig she is now associated with, having been withheld by the prison staff.
In 2015, there was still a positive response to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 project Stranger Visions.
In this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create images of possible faces of these people.
And just about this time, she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
'They were planning an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complement the article with a portrait,' explained Dewey-Hagborg at the opening of the new exhibition.
But visits and photographs were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, within days of the comic's release, President Obama asked for Manning's release, a welcome change after several harrowing years in a military prison in Kansas.
It's really interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war on people who seek to publish government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to use his tweets to incite resentment in the areas he is supposed to be promoting.
In response to questions about this peculiar timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for a reason".
Under the artist's statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls out with her huge signature (the letter i in the last name is spelled out with a heart) for an end to the self-created factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.
On the other side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - the letters C, G and A, written in pencil.
By arranging 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
'I hope people learn from this that our genome doesn't matter who we are and that genetic data is subjective and can be interpreted by anyone,' said Dewey-Hagborg.
DNA tells many different stories, and these are 30 of them.
The last exhibit in the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the graphic novel mentioned above.
It shows Manning coming out of the United States Disciplinary Barracks in King Kong style with a megaphone in her hand.
"As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win", it says.
Never let yourself be silenced.
"It's a direct copy of one of the letters", said the Philadelphia artist.
♪ When I think of it, my skin gets goose bumps. ♪
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition in person - as predicted in the comic - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room by her masks, her genomic portraits, lined up like a mob of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibit, including a nearly five-foot statue of Maning, with her genetic haplogroups written on it in pencil.
'In the past they have been placed on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel crowded,' Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement taking the form of Chelsea and liberating her.
