Startups that will help your company avoid the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the employee satisfaction rate of her e-commerce startup, but she couldn't find a relevant survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even misleading.
And even though she promised anonymity to the investigation, some of the staff expressed their distrust of the entire process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity", said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based hair-care e-commerce company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New startups in the human resources industry are constantly emerging in the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee engagement, startups enable companies to conduct rapid voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass their superiors and contact the CEO directly.
"There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glin, she had gained a greater awareness of what her employees were thinking and feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting for specific teams, Glint offers a company temperature map and a running overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - allowing users to work towards a fix.
Companies are starting to realize the need to care about workplace culture - in case they become another Uber - which is being swept up in scandals after a former employee posted a blog post describing the company environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture research presents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the technical and financial advancement website Let's Talk Payments, the global control, regulation and compliance industry could be worth over $118.8 billion by 2020.
A Denver, Colorado startup called Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect misconduct, saw a small surge of interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandal.
Convercent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, he's also taken Uber under his wing.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable flash surveys, gather confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behaviour.
If the Director-General is involved, complaints are sent directly to the Administrative Board.
"The court of public opinion has empowered regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the startup Convercent.
If a company is found to have misused its employees or engaged in unethical behavior - and if regulators don't step in - it could face costly consequences from customer boycott, staff attrition or litigation, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to raise employees' awareness of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he had to look up a phone number or e-mail address for the company's management, formally file a complaint, and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, the general representative for Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now, when a company uses Convercent, it's able to quickly detect and resolve issues that were never before addressed by managers sitting in offices, miles away from actually addressing complaints - such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair treatment.
'It's closer to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,' said Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's risk management oversight group.
At the same time, we protect shareholders from litigation by employees.
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following the collapse of Enron in a case of employee ethics abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until social media took over the business that companies started to realize that in the online world, they couldn't just hide their skeletons in the closet.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on beliefs", added Quinlan.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service for which the companies pay regular fees.
It's a business model and opportunity that's endorsed by the venture capitalists who backed both startups.
Convercent raised $10 million in its February campaign from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and ultimately took $47 million in equity.
Glint raised $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners and has raised $60 million over the course of the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interplay between companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets like Silicon Valley, it's not the high salaries and interesting projects that are the main advantage.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated and that they are giving their time to a company that is pursuing a positive mission.
"When people are happy in their work, feel that their voices are heard, and feel that their work is rewarding, they are driving the success of the company", said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when companies are doing well, and companies thrive when their employees are happy.
And when an analytical tool is introduced that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's no surprise that there are plenty of investors who will support that effort.
According to experts in work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But data alone is useless unless the company takes the necessary action.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if change doesn't happen quickly - in the worst case scenario - it can cause frustration and disengagement among employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations", said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has seen many companies rely too heavily on data alone.
Because when you don't get things done, employees start to wonder, did they hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'
Madison Reed, which now conducts a monthly employee survey, can solve the problem in a day, Errett said, thanks to Glinto.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and poor communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and initiate communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining very important insight into its employees and hopes that in the long run it will achieve high employment in a field known for frequent layoffs.
'If you don't work to create a transparent working environment, employees won't trust you,' Vitrano added.
And once you start losing employees, you're going to lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt.
