Facebook plans to tighten fact-checking to reduce the number of fake news
Facebook will send more potentially false articles to third-party reviewers and display findings under original posts in an effort to combat so-called "fake news", the largest social network said Thursday.
The company said in a statement on its website that it will begin using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes, send it to third parties for verification, and potentially display the survey results below the original posts.
Facebook has been called one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports influenced last year's election for president of the United States.
Political debates are raging across Europe: French voters are being inundated with fake news about the May presidential election, and Germany plans to fine the social media network before the September elections if it does not remove angry posts quickly.
Facebook said in a further statement issued in Germany on Thursday that it was going to start testing the new fake news feature in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
