The Making of a Graphic Novel: The Story of A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently featured in a music video by Squeeze and was a refuge for Margaret Thatcher during the 1970s and 1980s.
But from his cozy little hideaway on the River Bewl in Kent, England, Scotney witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history that inspired curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of Yorkshire, known for his fondness for historical documents, to create a graphic novel.
"The sight of the handwriting of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me", says Rhodes with a serious face.
When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of the families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period, each story illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
But this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by documents from the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was struck by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the '70s who worked for the Jacobites", he said.
It's his fingerprints!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read them.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love the archives!
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to spend almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, going through the archives, and studying the many treasures and curiosities, such as the hyenas' heads on the wall and bottles that had been thrown down the pit for centuries.
He would walk around the grounds and examine the ruins of the old castle, talking to the haymakers, the gardeners, and sometimes the artists who were working on the illustrations for his book.
He drank whiskey and salsa at night.
Scotney's private history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to the documents in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived on the scene ten years later, the staff were just beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described in words like aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands in the air, with the words, "Take it to the attic".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of property: "You may think a land dispute is boring", Rhodes said, "but I've come across one case where two families argued over a birch tree.
Stop it, people!
Some stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a rebellion at the castle in 1380, which was in a book called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex", Rhodes said.
The English rebellion actually started in this area and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're related after all.
Other stories are firmly tied to the castle's history - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was only discovered years later after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes's favorite family is the Darrell family: I was fascinated by the male generation - men were always in debt and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
The Darrells' various generations have dealt with this by marrying wealthy or old ladies - I imagine handsome gentlemen who liked to bash the heads of their heiresses.
With his stay at the castle over, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he was drawing inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that has been swallowed up by nature.
But for Scotney, it's a special place.
"I was sad when I left", he said.
I thought, "Now I'm going to get back to the real world".
