Red meat, dairy, and chocolate may alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study suggests the opposite: A diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 patients in the United Kingdom, it causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are usually reminded to avoid meat and dairy products to help relieve their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have discovered that the essential amino acid tryptophan found in protein helps to form immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, who led the study, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure that harmful microbes in food are eliminated.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales are tilted to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In the study, researchers found the presence of immune cells that promote body tolerance in the stomachs of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between a species of bacteria called Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a common part of the gut microbiome, and the development of cells that support the body's tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells they had.
He also suggested that if the same proved true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in studying a type of immune cell that promotes body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice kept separately lacked cells.
She deduced that one group of mice had a distinct gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice's intestines were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the other group of mice lacked.
Mice that were raised in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome -- they didn't develop that kind of immune cell -- were given L. reuteri bacteria -- and they developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells that were kept in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After the active substance was removed from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-octanoic acid.
