The White House acquisition cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to the South Lawn to celebrate American manufacturing industry last month came at a cost of $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One, with the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 White House program, a showcase of American engineering programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials were in attendance to view the product line from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was displayed alongside a Maine yacht, a fire engine from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a Fragmentary Order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn in an "emergency" event, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for managing the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event", the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an email to his superior, the Deputy Commander of Naval Aviation, the day before the event began.
The message indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn on July 17th at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m., and would remain in place until the entire site was cleared, which was scheduled to take place between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail also said that if there was a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement flight crew would be sent for the return flight due to the work schedule.
The original crew stayed in place that night with the helicopter and a security detail with them.
The recordings - obtained by TIME magazine - did not reveal whether a second crew was sent in after all.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We were wondering if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was in order", the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked", replied the deputy commander.
This "Made in America" parade was designated by the White House as an official event and would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political undertones.
In his speech, the president championed health care reform that had passed the Senate and spoke of trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of air transportation vehicles like Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence for presentational purposes alone is unusual.
Trump ordered the sweep in February after the presidential plane flew in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is pleased to host a 'Made in America' showcase of products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials", said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often practice landing in the Washington area and South Lawn and rehearse possible flights with the President of the United States to the White House with the utmost precision.
While Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The Made in America parade flight was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
The helicopter squadron flew another 11 hours of non-presidential support missions that same day.
The White House said no other taxpayer-funded props were paid for.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had no interest whatsoever in the talks to put the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 doesn't keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, reimbursing DoD for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit logs show a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico, Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopters are well below that amount.
To quote the cost to taxpayers based on estimates of reimbursement of expenditure is very misleading, Walters said.
These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.
The 2015 RAND study shows that DoD's reimbursement of expenses does not include personnel costs, but does include fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for the parade.
"The idea of the show this week is to showcase products made in the U.S"., Spicer said.
I'm aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide employment to hundreds if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we're proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens have helped to build.
This fact deserves to be remembered.
It's unclear whether Trump also looked at the helicopter during his tour of the South Lawn, but all we can say for sure is that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump approached a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well", said the President, "and I own three of them".
